&lt;p&gt;The coefficients are the projections of ğŸ in each basis direction (i.e., inner products), and then they&amp;rsquo;re multiplied with the unit vectors, and add them up.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;That means, in Fourier Series, the sines and cosines are the orthogonal basis functions.
Coefficients indicate how much ğŸ is in each direction.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;fourier-series-2&#34;&gt;Fourier Series-2
&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;Source video: &lt;a class=&#34;link&#34; href=&#34;https://youtu.be/Ud9Xtxsi2HI&#34;  target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;
    &gt;Fourier Series: Part 2&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;arbitrary-period-l&#34;&gt;Arbitrary period L
&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;Generalize the period from (-Ï€, Ï€) to (0, L)&lt;/p&gt;
$$
f(x) = \frac{Aâ‚€}{2} 
\    + âˆ‘â‚–â‚Œâ‚^âˆ (Aâ‚–cos( \frac{2Ï€kx}{L} ) + Bâ‚–sin( \frac{2Ï€kx}{L} ) )
$$&lt;p&gt;where:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;p&gt;cos( 2Ï€kx/L ) and sin( 2Ï€kx/L ) are periodic between 0 and L.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;p&gt;That is when x=0, 2Ï€kx/L=0, and when x=L, 2Ï€kx/L=2Ï€k, i.e., the wave returns to the start.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;p&gt;These cos( 2Ï€kx/L ) and sin( 2Ï€kx/L ) are orthogonal basis for Hilbert space of function f.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The Fourier coefficients change their bounds from (-Ï€, Ï€) to (0, L):&lt;/p&gt;
$$
Aâ‚– = \frac{2}{L} âˆ«_0^L f(x) cos(2Ï€kx/L) dx\\\
Bâ‚– = \frac{2}{L} âˆ«_0^L f(x) sin(2Ï€kx/L) dx
$$&lt;h3 id=&#34;approximation-is-periodic&#34;&gt;Approximation is periodic
