&lt;h2 id=&#34;complex-fourier-series&#34;&gt;Complex Fourier Series
&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;Source video: &lt;a class=&#34;link&#34; href=&#34;https://youtu.be/4cfctnaHyFM&#34;  target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;
    &gt;Complex Fourier Series&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Fourier series uses a infinite sum of sines and cosines functions of increasingly high frequencies to approximate an arbitrary &lt;strong&gt;periodic&lt;/strong&gt; function.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If the function is complex-valued, the Fourier series should be reformulated to accomondate imaginary numbers.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;By leveraging to Euler&amp;rsquo;s formula $e^{ikx} = cos(kx) + i sin(kx)$,
the complex Fourier series can be written as:&lt;/p&gt;
$$
f (x) = âˆ‘_{-âˆ}^{+âˆ} Câ‚– eâ±áµË£  \\\
\     = âˆ‘_{-âˆ}^{+âˆ} (Î±+Î²i) (cos(kx) + i sin(kx))
$$&lt;p&gt;where Câ‚– is a complex coefficient.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Real number is a subset of complex number, so this formula also adapt to read-valued functions, with subjecting to a constraint&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;if f(x) is real-valued, $Câ‚– = \bar Câ‚‹â‚–$.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This can be derived by expanding and kill all the imaginary terms:&lt;/p&gt;
$$
f(x) = âˆ‘_{-âˆ}^{+âˆ} (Î±+Î²i) (cos(kx) + i sin(kx)) \\\
\   = âˆ‘_{-âˆ}^{+âˆ} Î±cos(kx) + \cancel{ Î±i sin(kx) } + \cancel{ Î²icos(kx)} - Î²sin(kx) \\\
\   = âˆ‘_{-âˆ}^{+âˆ} Î±cos(kx) - Î²sin(kx) \\\
\   = âˆ‘_{-âˆ}^{+âˆ} (Î±-Î²i) (cos(-kx) + i sin(-kx) ) \\\
$$&lt;h3 id=&#34;eâ±áµË£-are-orthogonal-basis&#34;&gt;eâ±áµË£ are Orthogonal basis
&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;eâ±áµË£ with taking different integer k stands for different basis function.
And these basis functions are orthogonal, which are unique directions and form an infinite-dimensional function space.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Orthogonal means the inner products against each other are 0, but the inner product with itself is its norm squared.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Let eâ±áµË£ be defined as Î¨â‚– (eâ±áµË£ â‰” Î¨â‚–), then the inner product in the Hilbert space of any two basis functions can be computed as an integral
(the period is [-Ï€,Ï€]):&lt;/p&gt;
$$
âŸ¨Î¨â±¼, Î¨â‚–âŸ© = âˆ«_{-Ï€}^Ï€ Î¨â±¼ â‹… \bar Î¨â‚– dx  \\\
\       = âˆ«_{-Ï€}^Ï€  eâ±Ê²Ë£ â‹… eâ»â±áµË£ dx  \\\
\       = âˆ«_{-Ï€}^Ï€  eâ±â½Ê²â»áµâ¾Ë£ dx \\\
\       = \frac{1}{i(j-k)} â‹… [eâ±â½Ê²â»áµâ¾Ë£ ]_{-Ï€}^Ï€
$$&lt;p&gt;if (k-j) is non-zero, but an integar d, and because eâ±áµˆ$^Ï€$ = eâ±áµˆ$^{-Ï€}$, the inner product (definite integral) is 0.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;While if (k-j)=0, the inner product is 0/0:&lt;/p&gt;
$$
\frac{ [eâ±â½Ê²â»áµâ¾Ë£]_{-Ï€}^Ï€ }{ i(j-k) } = \frac{0}{0} 
$$&lt;p&gt;According to Loptial&amp;rsquo;s Rule, &amp;quot; the limit of the ratio of two functions is the same after we take the derivative of each function.&amp;quot;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So take the derivative of numerator and denominator w.r.t. (j-k):&lt;/p&gt;
$$
\begin{aligned}
&amp; lim_{(j-k)â†’0} \frac{ [eâ±â½Ê²â»áµâ¾Ë£ ]\_{-Ï€}^Ï€ }{ i(j-k) } \\\
&amp;= lim_{(j-k)â†’0} \frac{e^{i(j-k)Ï€} - e^{i(j-k)(-Ï€)} }{i(j-k)} \\\
&amp;= lim_{(j-k)â†’0} \frac{ iÏ€ e^{i(j-k)Ï€} - (-Ï€i)  e^{i(j-k)(-Ï€)}}{i}  \\\
&amp;= 2Ï€
\end{aligned}
$$&lt;p&gt;Actually, it&amp;rsquo;s not necessary to take this limit.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Since $âŸ¨Î¨â±¼, Î¨â‚–âŸ© = âˆ«_{-Ï€}^Ï€  eâ±â½Ê²â»áµâ¾Ë£ dx$, this integral = 2Ï€ when (j-k) = 0.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the inner product is&lt;/p&gt;
$$
âŸ¨Î¨â±¼, Î¨â‚–âŸ© = \frac{1}{i(j-k)} â‹… eâ±â½Ê²â»áµâ¾Ë£ |_{-Ï€}^Ï€ \\\
\ =
\begin{cases}
0 &amp; \text{if j $\neq$ k} \\\
2Ï€ &amp; \text{if j=k}
\end{cases}
$$&lt;p&gt;The norm squared of a basis function Î¨â±¼ (â€–Î¨â±¼â€–Â²) is 2Ï€.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Analogy to regular 2D vector space &lt;a class=&#34;link&#34; href=&#34;#projection--reconstruction&#34; &gt;above&lt;/a&gt;, a function can be written as a sum of projections that the function is projected onto each basis function:&lt;/p&gt;
$$
ğŸ(x) = âˆ‘_{-âˆ}^{+âˆ} Câ‚– eâ±áµË£ = âˆ‘_{k=-âˆ}^{+âˆ} \frac{âŸ¨ğŸ(x), Î¨â‚–âŸ©}{2Ï€} â‹…Î¨â‚–
$$&lt;p&gt;&lt;font color=&#34;red&#34;&gt;doubt&lt;/font&gt;:
Is Î¨â‚– unit length? Otherwise, Î¨â‚– needs normalization?, because the 1/2Ï€ is for energy measurement instead of getting the unit length of Î¨â‚–?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The intuitive application of Fourier series is that: &lt;strong&gt;given&lt;/strong&gt; a function, the approximated version of it can be obtained by truncating the summation of basis direction weighted by coefficients.
And the coefficients is the projection (inner product) of the function onto each basis.&lt;/p&gt;
